properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Continues For The Red River From Emerson To The Red River Floodway Channel Inlet
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre continues to issue a Flood Warning on the Red River from Emerson to the Red River Floodway channel inlet due to high water flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions given by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-04-26T11:30:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-04-25T11:40:06-05:00, 6FE793C2-E928-A9AA-439C-F389B2C8AD4E
Area: Red River from Emerson to the Red River Floodway channel inlet
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Another significant rainfall Friday. Rain, heavy at times, will move into Eastern Ontario Friday morning and continue into Friday evening. Total rainfall amounts of 20 to 35 millimetres are forecast by Saturday morning. Flood messaging is in effect for much of Eastern Ontario. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local Conservation Authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry District office. This heavy rain is associated with a Texas low that will track across Southern Ontario on Friday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Late season snow A transition to a showery pattern will begin across central and eastern BC on Friday evening as a trough of low pressure crosses the province. Freezing levels will drop in the wake of the system on Saturday causing rain showers to switch over to snow, particularly over the high mountain passes. 5 cm of snow will fall by early Saturday morning over Pine Pass where the transition from rain to snow will occur the earliest. 5 to 10 cm of snow is expected over the higher elevations of the Trans-Canada highway including Rogers Pass. The Elk Valley could also see 5 to 10 cm of snow on Saturday. Late season snow is also expected over Yoho with approximately 5 cm. Drier conditions are expected on Sunday. Motorists are encouraged to be prepared for winter driving conditions and consult DriveBC for road conditions before travelling. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2019-04-26T06:13:58-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-04-25T22:14:58-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1595159241.2019
Area: Highway 97 - Pine Pass, Trans-Canada Highway - Eagle Pass to Rogers Pass
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain on Friday and on Saturday. Rain will begin midday Friday over Southern Quebec and will intensify overnight Friday night as it spreads eastward. Conditions will gradually improve late in the day on Saturday. Rainfall amounts in the 15- to 30-millimetre range are expected south of the St Lawrence River and Mont-Tremblant as well as over the Lower St Lawrence, the Saguenay-Lac-St-Jean and the North Shore. Combined with the melting snowpack, the rain is expected to accelerate the spring freshet. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
Expires: 2019-04-26T10:39:09-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-04-26T02:40:09-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2928780698.2019
